
<section>
  <title>Factoring trinomials when <m>a=1</m></title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      In the previous section we saw how we could factor certain polynomials by grouping. In this section, we look at
      trinomials that have a leading coefficient<index><main>coefficient</main></index> of <m>1</m>. Remember that in our previous modules we used the FOIL<index><main>FOIL</main></index> method
      to expand binomial products. We considered examples such as
      <md>
        <mrow>(x+1)(x+3) \amp  =    x^2+3x+x+3</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp  =    x^2+4x+3</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      The goal of this section is to develop the skills to go from the right hand side in the above (a trinomial<index><main>trinomial</main></index>), to the left hand side-
      in other words, to factor the trinomial.
    </p>

    <p>
      There are a number of important observations that will help us to factor trinomials. We
      begin with a review of FOILing.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection>
    <title>FOILing review</title>
    <p>
      We begin with a review of multiplying binomials using the FOIL method. Once we review
      how the trinomial was put together it may be easier to see how to take it apart
    </p>
