      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      Notice that the product of the first terms always yielded a squared term. Notice that the last
      term of the trinomial is always the product of the two number. The middle term is found
      by adding the O and I columns.
    </p>

    <p>
      Another helpful hint is to look at the signs of the terms for the trinomial compared to the signs
      for the binomials. When the signs (connectors) between the terms is the same (as in examples A and B),
      the middle terms of the trinomial matches this same sign. In fact adding the middle terms always gives
      the numerical value for the middle.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the signs (connectors) between the terms are different, as in examples C and D, the middle
      term could end up either sign. Looking at example C, we see that the middle term is negative
      because the larges in absolute value <m>6</m> was negative. The numerical value is the
      difference of the two numbers. In example D, we see that the middle term was positive because
      <m>4>3</m>, and 4 is a positive number. Using these sign rules will help you eliminate
      many of the guesses you will need to make.
    </p>

    <definition>
      <statement>
        <ul>
          <li><p>
              if the numbers are the same sign then the middle term is the sum, and same sign as the last term
            </p></li>

          <li><p>
              if the numbers are different signs, then the middle term is the difference, and the sign is the same
                  largest absolute value
            </p></li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </definition>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Products and sums of numbers</title>
    <p>
      We begin with an exercise in sums and products. Consider the following table
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Two numbers</cell>
        <cell>{Their product}</cell>
        <cell>{Their sum}</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>6</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>9</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>-9</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      In the left hand column, we wish to find two numbers that when multiplied together, give the middle column, and
      when added together, give the third column. So we can fill in the first entry by noting that
      <me>
        4+2=6,
      </me>
      and
      <me>
        4\cdot 2=8
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      So the numbers that we need to put into the first column are
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Two numbers</cell>
        <cell>{Their product}</cell>
        <cell>{Their sum}</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>{\color{blue}4, 2}</cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>6</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>9</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>-9</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      Note: choosing <m>4</m> and <m>2</m> was a very good first guess. In fact there are other factors of <m>8</m> such as
      <m>8</m> and <m>1</m>, but these clearly give <m>8+1=9</m>, which is not <m>6</m> (the required sum).
    </p>

    <p>
      Similarly, in the second row we want two numbers that when multiplied together give <m>8</m>, and when
      added together give 9. We see that the required numbers are <m>8</m> and <m>1</m>, since
      <me>
        8+1=9, \qquad 8*1=8
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      We can therefore fill in the next row of our table
    </p>
    <tabular>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Two numbers</cell>
        <cell>{Their product}</cell>
        <cell>{Their sum}</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>{\color{blue}4, 2}</cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>6</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>{\color{blue}8, 1}</cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>9</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>8</cell>
        <cell>-9</cell>
      </row>
      <row bottom="minor">
        <cell></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
    <p>
      The last row is interesting, as the product is <em>negative</em>, and yet their product is still <em>positive</em>. Remember
      from elementary arithmetic, that a negative number times a negative number is a positive. For example
      <me>
        (-2)(-5)=10.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      We use this result in the last row of the table. The factors of 8 are
      <me>
        1, 8, \qquad 2,4,  \qquad -2, -4, \qquad -8, -1.
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      The only pair that adds up to -9 is -8 and -1. So we complete the final row of the table with
    </p>
