    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor
          <me>
            x^2+7x+10
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <solution>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
            First we determine the signs on the connectors of each binomial. Since
                the middle term and the last term are positive, we will have
            <me>
              (+)(+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Next we determine where the first term (product) could have come from. 
                The choices are only <m>x</m> and <m>x</m>.
            <me>
              (x+)(x+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            To determine the numbers, we need to look at the last term. Since this will
                be the product of the factors, we need to write the number as the product of possible
                factors
            <me>
              10 = 10(1)  \qquad 10 = 5 \cdot 2
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Since the middle term is <m>7</m> we know that we need the sum of the factors to be 7. 
                So we therefore try
            <me>
              (x+5)(x+2)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            We should check our answer using the FOIL technique (exercise).
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Because of the commutative property of multiplication, the answer can also be written as
            <me>
              (x+2)(x+5)
            </me>
          </p></li>
      </ul>
    </solution>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor
          <me>
            x^2-14x+45
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <solution>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
            First we determine the signs on the connectors of each binomial. Since
                the middle term and the last term are negative, we will have
            <me>
              (-)(-)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Next we determine where the first term (product) could have come from. 
                The choices are only <m>x</m> and <m>x</m>.
            <me>
              (x-)(x-)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            To determine the numbers, we need to look at the last term. Since this will
                be the product of the factors, we need to write the number as the product of possible
                factors
            <me>
              45=45(1)\qquad 45=3(15)\qquad 5(9)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Since the middle term is <m>-14</m> we know that we need the sum of the factors to be -14. 
                So we therefore try
            <me>
              (x-5)(x-9)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            We should check our answer using the FOIL technique (exercise).
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Because of the commutative property of multiplication, the answer can also be written as
            <me>
              (x-9)(x-5)
            </me>
          </p></li>
      </ul>
    </solution>
    <example xml:id="ex_factoring1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor
          <me>
            y^2+5y-24
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <solution>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
            First we determine the signs on the connectors of each binomial. Since
                the middle term is positive, and the last term is negative, we will have
            <me>
              (-)(+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Next we determine where the first term (product) could have come from. 
                The choices are only <m>y</m> and <m>y</m>.
            <me>
              (y-)(y+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            To determine the numbers, we need to look at the last term. Since this will
                be the product of the factors, we need to write the number as the product of possible
                factors
                <m>-24 = -1(24)\qquad -24=-24(1) \qquad -24=-12(2) \qquad -24=-2(12)</m> 

                  <m>-24 = -8(3) \qquad -24=-3(8)\qquad -24=-6(4) \qquad -24 = -4(6)</m>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Since the middle term is <m>5</m> we know that we need the sum of the factors to be <m>5</m>.
                So we therefore try
            <me>
              (y-3)(y+8)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            We should check our answer using the FOIL technique (exercise).
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Because of the commutative property of multiplication, the answer can also be written as
            <me>
              (y+8)(y-3)
            </me>
          </p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Note: if we had tried
        <me>
          (y+3)(y-8)
        </me>
        then this would not have worked, as the O and I terms from FOIL do not add together to give <m>5</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor
          <me>
            w^2+12w-64
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <solution>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
            First we determine the signs on the connectors of each binomial. Since
                the middle term is positive, and the last term is negative, we will have
            <me>
              (-)(+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Next we determine where the first term (product) could have come from. 
                The choices are only <m>x</m> and <m>x</m>.
            <me>
              (x-)(x+)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            To determine the numbers, we need to look at the last term. Since this will
                be the product of the factors, we need to write the number as the product of possible
                factors
                <m>-64=-64(1)\qquad -64=-1(64)\qquad -64=-32(2) \qquad -64 = -2(32)</m>

                  <m>-64=-16(4)\qquad -64 = -4(16)\qquad -64 = -8(8)</m>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Since the middle term is <m>12</m> we know that we need the sum of the factors to be <m>12</m>.
                So we therefore try
            <me>
              (x-4)(x+16)
            </me>
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            We should check our answer using the FOIL technique (exercise).
          </p></li>

        <li><p>
            Because of the commutative property of multiplication, the answer can also be written as
            <me>
              (x+16)(x-4)
            </me>
          </p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Note: in this example there were quite a few different options to choose from. This is typical, and you
        should expect to do some trial error for each exercise. Experience and practise will help to guide you.
      </p>
    </solution>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Factor
          <me>
            2x^2+10x-48
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <solution>
      <p>
        At first glance, it may appear that this example should not be in this section, as <m>a\ne 1</m>; however, we note
        that as a first step we may remove a factor of 2 from each term
        <me>
          2x^2+10x-48 = 2(x^2+5x-24)
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        We recognize the expression within the () as <xref ref="ex_factoring1" autoname="yes" /> (except with <m>x</m> instead of <m>y</m>),
        so we can complete this example as follows
        <me>
          2(x^2+5x-24)  =  2(x+8)(x-3)
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        As in the previous examples, we should check our answer by FOILing (exercise).
      </p>
    </solution>
